# Chapter 13 — Wireless Technology
### (Cybersecurity / Ethical Hacking Perspective)

Wireless networking is one of the **highest-value chapters for practical ethical hacking** — WiFi hacking is a core skill tested in CEH, OSCP, and real-world red team engagements. This chapter builds directly on Chapter 8 (unguided media).

---

## 1. What Is Wireless Technology?

Communication using radio frequency (RF) signals instead of physical cables — includes WiFi, Bluetooth, NFC, and cellular. The core security challenge: **the "cable" is the open air, reachable by anyone in range.**

---

## 2. WiFi Standards (802.11 Family)

| Standard | Band | Max Speed | Security Note |
|---|---|---|---|
| 802.11b/g | 2.4 GHz | Up to 54 Mbps | Older, more interference, still widely deployed (legacy risk) |
| 802.11n | 2.4/5 GHz | Up to 600 Mbps | Introduced WPA2 as standard expectation |
| 802.11ac | 5 GHz | Up to ~1.3 Gbps | Common in modern routers |
| 802.11ax (WiFi 6) | 2.4/5/6 GHz | Multi-Gbps | Supports WPA3 |

