## 7. Why This Matters for Ethical Hacking

- WiFi hacking is one of the most commonly tested practical skills in CEH and OSCP-style certifications.
- Physical proximity attacks (evil twin, deauth) are realistic and low-cost — no need for remote exploitation, just being nearby.
- Enterprise wireless assessments are a standard part of physical red team/pentest engagements (parking lot attacks, testing guest WiFi isolation).

---

## Quick Revision Points
- WEP = broken; WPA2 = strong if passphrase is strong; WPA3 = current best standard.
- Most real-world WPA2 attacks target the passphrase via captured handshakes, not the encryption algorithm.
- Deauth attacks, evil twin APs, and WPS PIN attacks are the three most practical/common wireless attack vectors.
- Bluetooth has its own attack class: bluejacking, bluesnarfing, bluebugging.
- Defensive best practice: WPA3/WPA2-AES, disable WPS, strong passphrases, 802.1X for enterprise, monitor for rogue APs.

